Frontend
This file defines strict rules, standards, and best practices for all front-end code, documentation, and project tasks. It ensures the code is professional, modular, semantic, maintainable, and fully aligned with back-end APIs and services.

1. General Principles

TypeScript Only: All front-end code must be written in TypeScript.

Strict Typing: All types/interfaces must be defined in dedicated files (types.ts) under src/types/ or feature-specific folders. Never inline types in components.

No Hard-Coding: Do not hard-code strings, keys, or magic values. Store constants in src/constants/ and import them.

Separation of Concerns: Keep UI, business logic, API calls, and helpers/utilities in separate files.

Modularity: Organize code by feature/domain. Use folders for complex components and hooks.

Reusability: Build small, composable, and reusable components/hooks.

2. API Integration

Centralized API Services: All API calls must use a shared Axios instance (src/api/axios.ts).

Endpoints Constants: Define all endpoints in src/constants/endpoints.ts. Do not hard-code URLs.

Error Handling: Use standardized utilities like handleApiError.

React Query / SWR: Use TanStack React Query (useQuery, useMutation) for all data fetching and mutations.

Custom Hooks: Encapsulate API logic in src/hooks/domain/. Components must never call APIs directly.

Typed Payloads: All requests and responses must be typed.

Extending APIs: Follow existing patterns when adding new endpoints or methods.

3. Form Handling

Formik + Yup: Use Formik for state management and Yup for validation.

Validation Schemas: Keep schemas in separate files (schema.ts or validation.ts).

Reusable Fields: Use shared input components for consistency.

No Inline Validation: Validation logic should not be inside components.

Multi-Step Forms: Use context or local state for step management; keep each step modular.

4. UI Components

Component Structure:

Shared components → src/components/common/

Feature-specific → their respective folders

Props & Types: All props must use interfaces from separate type files.

Styling: Tailwind CSS utility classes preferred. For complex styling, use CSS modules or global styles.

No Inline Handlers: Move all functions to helpers or hooks.

Custom Hooks: Group related logic; avoid multiple related functions in component bodies.

Exports: Use index.ts in component folders for cleaner imports.

Testing: Add unit tests where possible; otherwise verify manually.

5. Project Structure

Feature-Based: Organize code by domain/feature for scalability.

Dedicated Folders: Use folders for API, components, hooks, context/providers, types, schemas, utils, constants.

Pages/Routes: Put pages/routes in src/pages/ (Next.js) or src/views/ (Vue).

Global State: Use React Context, Zustand, or Redux providers for shared/global state.

6. Constants & Enums

Centralized: Store all constants, enums, keys in src/constants/.

No Duplicates: Never duplicate values; import from the central source.

7. Helpers & Utilities

Location: Place reusable helpers in src/utils/ or feature-specific utils/ folders.

No Inline Logic: Do not define non-trivial logic inside components or services.

8. Third-Party Integrations

Encapsulation: Wrap all third-party service logic in hooks, services, or context.

API Keys: Keep all API keys and secrets in environment variables (.env).

Documentation: Document setup and usage in doc/third_party_integration.md.

9. Documentation & Comments

Doc Files: Update or create docs for all new modules/features.

JSDoc: Document all exported functions, classes, and complex logic.

Usage Examples: Include examples for complex components/modules.

10. Design Patterns & Professionalism

Semantic Naming: Use descriptive, semantic names for variables, functions, and files.

Professional Structure: Follow modularity, separation of concerns, and maintainability best practices.

Avoid Anti-Patterns: No shortcuts, duplicated logic, or code smells.

Consistency: Follow established patterns; document new patterns.

11. Task-Specific Rules

Adding a Module: Follow doc/project_structure.md and doc/api_integration.md.

Creating Forms: Follow doc/form_handling.md.

Building UI Components: Follow doc/ui_component_and_project_tasks.md.

Integrating Third-Party Services: Follow doc/third_party_integration.md.

Always: Follow rules in this file for all new and refactored code.

12. Enforcement

Mandatory: All rules are mandatory for contributors and AI agents.

Review: All code must be reviewed for compliance before merge or deployment.

13. Quick Reference

Types/Interfaces: types.ts

Constants/Enums: constants.ts

API: src/api/, src/constants/endpoints.ts

Forms: Formik + Yup, separate schema files

UI: Typed, modular, Tailwind, no inline logic

Docs: Update doc/ files for all new modules or changes

API Calls: Always use endpoint constants, never hard-code URLs

Historical Reminder: Avoid previously observed mistakes like hard-coded endpoints in services; always import from constants.

BACKEND
1. Core Principles

The system must be maintainable, scalable, and reliable.

All code and architecture must follow Laravel best practices and PHP standards.

Adhere to key software engineering principles:

DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself): Avoid duplication; centralize logic in services, traits, or helpers.

KISS (Keep It Simple, Stupid): Favor straightforward solutions; avoid unnecessary abstraction.

YAGNI (You Aren’t Gonna Need It): Implement only what is needed now.

Single Responsibility Principle: Each class, controller, or method should have one clear responsibility.

Separation of Concerns: Keep Controllers, Models, Services, and Requests separate; do not mix logic.

Ensure all changes support long-term maintainability of the codebase.

2. General Best Practices

Always validate user permissions and ownership before update, delete, or sensitive read operations.

Use try/catch blocks and Laravel’s logging (Log::error()) for all exception-prone operations.

Use enums/constants for statuses, roles, and types.

Document all new routes, models, services, and business logic in the backend documentation.

Use Eloquent or query builder for all DB access; never write raw SQL in controllers.

Write modular, single-responsibility classes and methods.

Store all environment-specific values in .env.

Backward Compatibility: Avoid breaking changes for existing routes, APIs, and database structures.

Do not use SELECT *; always select explicit columns in queries for clarity and performance.

3. Architectural Layers
3.1. Routes & Controllers

Validate all incoming requests using Form Requests.

Return consistent JSON responses with HTTP status codes.

Controllers must delegate business logic to services.

Document all endpoints with request/response schemas.

3.2. Services

Handle core business logic here.

Emit events and notifications for major actions (e.g., model creation, update).

Validate and sanitize all inputs before processing.

Use dependency injection where applicable.

3.3. Repositories

Abstract database operations for reusability.

Use transactions for multi-step operations.

Validate ownership and permissions before updates or deletes.

Handle errors and log context clearly.

3.4. Requests/Validators

Define request validation rules using Laravel Form Requests.

Validate required fields, types, and constraints.

Reuse rules across endpoints where possible.

3.5. Migrations & Seeders

All schema changes must use Laravel migrations (php artisan make:migration).

Follow timestamped migration filenames (YYYY_MM_DD_HHMMSS_description).

Seeders should be idempotent and documented.

Never alter an already-run migration; create a new one for changes.

3.6. Events & Notifications

Use Laravel Events & Listeners for cross-service communication and notifications.

Persist notifications in the database even if no real-time listener is connected.

Validate event payloads to ensure data integrity.

3.7. Utils, Traits, and Helpers

Write stateless, reusable helper functions or traits.

Document input/output clearly.

Avoid duplication across services.

3.8. Config & Constants

Store all repeated values in config/ files or enums.

Use .env for sensitive or environment-specific data.

Document all configuration options.

4. Service-Specific Rules (Example Services)
4.1. Lead Service

Emit events for creation, status updates, and important actions.

Use notifications for relevant users/teams.

Validate required fields and state transitions.

Document flows in backend documentation.

4.2. Payment Service

Update related models when logging payments.

Notify relevant users/departments for significant events.

Use constants/enums for types and statuses.

Log events for auditing purposes.

4.3. Appointment Service

Emit events for status changes, assignment, and deletion.

Integrate with other modules for assignment logic.

Validate permissions before updates.

Document all flows and events.

4.4. Team/User Service

Check for duplicate emails or usernames.

Use hashed passwords and secure token generation.

Validate permissions before updates/deletes.

Notify users for status changes or important updates.

4.5. AI & Chat Services

Emit events for call/chat actions.

Sanitize sensitive data in logs.

Validate extracted data before updating leads or tasks.

Document all new features, events, and notifications.

4.6. Chatter/Comment Service

Emit notifications for mentions, comments, and updates.

Validate existence of parent models before adding attachments.

Use enums/constants for event types.

Document new templates and notifications.

5. Security

Never log or expose sensitive data (passwords, tokens, PII).

Use Laravel hashing (Hash::make) and token generation.

Sanitize and validate all user input.

6. Logging

Use Log::info() / Log::error() for all logs.

Include user ID and request ID where applicable.

Do not log sensitive information.

7. API Versioning

All new APIs must be versioned (/api/v1/).

Migrate existing APIs gradually to versioned routes.

8. Dependency Management

Use Composer for dependency management.

Check for duplicates before adding packages.

Keep dependencies updated (composer outdated && composer update).

9. Code Formatting

Use PHP CS Fixer or PHP_CodeSniffer for formatting.

Follow PSR-12 standards.

Configure IDE for automatic formatting on save.

10. Dry Run Verification & Documentation

Pre-Implementation Analysis: Trace data flow (Request → Controller → Service → Repository → Model → DB → Event/Notification).

Post-Implementation Verification: Confirm data integrity, business logic, and correct event emission.

Verification Checklist:

 Input validation

 Business logic correctness

 DB storage/retrieval

 API responses match schema

 Error handling works

 Events/notifications are correct

Document expected data structures and verification steps in BACKEND_DOCUMENTATION.md.

11. Contribution Guidelines

Perform data flow analysis before implementing new features.

Refactor while maintaining data integrity.

Submit PRs with:

Clear descriptions

Data flow verification

Event/notification updates

All code changes must pass verification before merge.

12. Cron Jobs (Scheduled Tasks)

Use Laravel Scheduler (app/Console/Kernel.php) for periodic tasks.

Do not use cron jobs for user-triggered actions.

Document schedule, purpose, and methods called.

Ensure correctness and avoid side effects.

13. Database Performance & Indexing

Only add indexes for performance-critical queries.

Focus on login/auth and frequent queries first.

Document purpose and expected performance impact of new indexes.

Monitor query performance post-deployment.